Just as a hobbyist for fun, fame: just because I can. But in this world things like that are a luxury: with that in mind please enjoy this small write up that aims to help people with basic computer security for the web.

This is is web security defense for mere mortals....

So everyone whom aims at good security on a deep technical level will tell you that it is best in layers, and maybe that can
work for people that are programmers, security people or system admins(maybe). But the much like the mantra same origin policy (if you're not sure what that is: https://developer.mozilla.org/en-US/docs/Web/Security/Defenses/Same-origin_policy) it is the "user" that needs we fight for! Let's take a bit of a deep dive(without getting too technical) into browser security.

For most people, a browser is just a window to the internet. Chrome, Firefox, Safari—whatever:
To mere mortals, browsers are simple: you click, you search, you watch videos, you shop, you live online.
But beneath that friendly search bar lies one of the most complex, attack-prone pieces of software ever shipped to billions of people. Browsers juggle JavaScript engines, rendering pipelines, extension ecosystems, GPU interfaces, sandbox layers, networking stacks, and dozens of built-in APIs—all running tens of thousands of lines of code every time a webpage loads
And for a decade straight, attackers have treated browsers as a prime hunting ground.
The stories below—spanning 2015 through 2025—show how browser attacks evolved from noisy adware pop-ups and shady Flash exploits into silent, surgical zero-days and billion-user supply-chain compromises.
This is the story of how clicking a link became a geopolitical hazard, how a wallpaper extension became a remote-control hacking tool, and how your browser became the most important (and most dangerous) program you own.

THE ERA OF EXPLOIT KITS (2015-17) When Ads Tried to Kill You

Back in 2015, the danger came not from the websites you visited, but from the ads those websites trusted. Attackers built industrial-scale “exploit kits” like Angler, Nuclear, and RIG, which hid inside banner ads on legitimate news and shopping sites that the website(s) you where trying to visit in the could not see(in many cases). You did not need to click the ad. You didn’t even need to see it. If the malicious JavaScript loaded, the exploit kit scanned your browser, Flash plugin, Java plugin, and Windows version. If you matched one of their vulnerabilities—boom: ransomware, banking Trojans, botnet malware, whatever they wanted. 
It was the Wild West of “malvertising.” Entire ad networks became the new crime infrastructure. Millions of users were infected in this era, often without ever understanding what happened. This is also the era when people said, “Just don’t click anything suspicious,” not realizing that doing nothing at all could still compromise them. 

Spectre & Meltdown (2018): When Browsers Became a CPU Threat Surface

January 2018 delivered one of the most surreal discoveries in modern computing: CPU hardware flaws that allowed malicious JavaScript to read memory it should never have touched. Your browser—yes, the place you watch cat videos—could be tricked into leaking passwords, encryption keys, and sensitive data through microscopic timing differences in JavaScript execution. The web responded with: Reduced JavaScript timers, site isolation and Emergency browser updates across the globe. This was the moment browsers became treated like full operating systems, not just viewers of information.

Chrome & Firefox Zero-Days (2018–2019): The Rise of Targeted Exploitation

By 2018 and 2019, attackers shifted heavily toward memory corruption vulnerabilities in browser engines themselves—especially:
Chrome’s V8 engine, Firefox’s IonMonkey JIT compiler these were not spam campaigns or random infections. These were surgical, often nation-state-level attacks. A single malicious website or link—sometimes sent privately to journalists, activists, or political targets—could trigger a chain of memory corruption bugs, eventually letting the attacker run arbitrary code outside the browser sandbox. This era marked the beginning of “zero-days as weapons.” 

THE SUPPLY-CHAIN REVOLUTION (2020–2024) 

When the Attackers Took Over the Update System as browsers hardened their engines and exploit kits faded, attackers found a more elegant path: Why break into the browser when you can hijack the code people voluntarily install? Extensions Become Malware Factories Browser extensions became the new frontier of exploitation. Why? Because users install them for: discounts, emojis, wallpapers, “Free coupons”, productivity tools(now mostly replaced by A.I) all of which quietly request permissions like: “Read and change all your data on all websites”, “Access your browser tabs”, “Manage your downloads”,Most users click “Allow” without thinking., This trust set the stage for the most dramatic example of all…


THE SHADYPANDA ERA (2023–2025):

The Long Con That Let Hackers In Through the Front Door, imagine installing a harmless wallpaper extension in 2019. It works fine.
You forget it exists. Five years later—it turns into a hacking tool. That’s ShadyPanda, a massive multi-year browser-extension supply-chain compromise revealed in late 2025. Extensions with millions of installs—some verified, some featured—slowly received “updates” that added: Cookie theft, Session hijacking, Search redirection, data exfiltration, remote code execution via downloaded JavaScript, And it all happened through the official Chrome and Edge extension update systems. No phishing. no shady downloads. No suspicious behavior: just seemingly normal updates. It’s the perfect crime: exploit people’s trust in the platform.

MODERN ZERO-DAY WARFARE (2025):
When Clicking a Link Was Enough to Get Hacked, 2025 became the most active year for browser zero-days in recent history.
Multiple high-severity bugs in Chrome’s V8 engine, along with a critical Mojo IPC sandbox escape, were exploited in the wild—often by advanced threat actors: CVE-2025-2783 — Sandboxed attacked via malicious link Used in “Operation ForumTroll,” targeting journalists and political organizations. CVE-2025-6554 — V8 type confusion, Allowed crafted HTML to break memory protections and run code. CVE-2025-13223 — Heap corruption RCE, Another attack via simple webpage load. In several cases, the victim merely clicked a link—or visited a compromised site—and the exploit chain executed invisibly. This marked the full maturation of the “drive-by” attack, now powered not by ad networks or plugins, but deep engine-level vulnerabilities. 

