TAKEAWAYS FOR MERE MORTALS:
Browsers have become full operating systems, not simple viewers, JavaScript engines (V8, SpiderMonkey) are incredibly complex—and incredibly attackable. Extensions are the new Trojan horses. Automatic updates are both your greatest defense and a terrifying attack surface. A single click on a malicious link can compromise the entire machine. Modern attacks leave no pop-ups, no weird behavior, no crash alerts—nothing. The average user doesn’t have to panic—just stay updated, be cautious with extensions, and treat your browser like the critical, high-risk application it is... I don't write this to spread FUD(fear uncertainty doubt), I do so that the information is out there for people to have that knowledge and that it will help them to be more secure.

Some things that may help with this are no-script: https://noscript.net 

Sorry I know it's a hard sell to mere mortals but I really will help protect you from allot of these kinds of things, there is also a light version of it too that's a bit more user friendly.

Just generally having a good password very random password like "x829u8Qin8d!" and making sure to not re-use passwords.

But the number one thing that will help save you as a user is just general common sense when It comes to making informed choices about the company's that you give your data too... you can't steal the data of a person whom did not give real data that could be tied from their online life to their real one. That information is only valuable to hackers/company's so much as they can use it!


